  "text": "For those middle level target parts that were matched strongly onto candidates in the new frame, the feature models are updated according to new observations. Note that any kind of target model relearning is potentially dangerous, since even small tracking errors can easily cause background pixels to be learned into the target model, leading to instability with exponentially increasing errors. Early colour particle filter work [CITATION_1] , and recent state-of-the-art patch-based methods [CITATION_2] , perform model relearning at a fixed update speed. In contrast, we continuously recompute individual update speeds for each middle level target part at each frame. Our premise is that parts can be relearned rapidly when there is a high confidence in their matching, whereas the relearning rate should be reduced under conditions of uncertainty. We therefore update each patch, using a continuously relearned parameter, µ i mid (p) k , according to the following update rule:",
